4:
He insulted me,
hit me,
beat me,
robbed me &mdash;
for those who dont brood on this,
	hostility is stilled.

162:
When overspread by extreme vice &mdash;
like a sal tree by a vine &mdash;
you do to yourself
what an enemy would wish.

175:
Swans fly the path of the sun;
those with the power fly through space;
the enlightened flee from the world,
having defeated the armies of Mara.

180:
In whom theres no craving
 &mdash; the sticky ensnarer &mdash;
to lead him anywherever at all;
awakened, his pasture endless,
	pathless:
by what path will you lead him astray?

223:
Conquer anger
	with lack of anger;
bad, with good;
stinginess, with a gift;
a liar, with truth.

224:
By telling the truth;
by not growing angry;
by giving, when asked,
no matter how little you have:
by these three things
you enter the presence of devas.

234:
Those restrained in body
	&mdash; the enlightened &mdash;
restrained in speech &amp; in mind
	&mdash; enlightened &mdash;
are the ones whose restraint is secure.

244:
Lifes easy to live
for someone unscrupulous,
	cunning as a crow,
	corrupt, back-biting,
	forward, & brash;

258:
Simply talking a lot
doesnt mean one is wise.
Whoevers secure &mdash;
	no     hostility,
	   fear &mdash;
is said to be wise.

308:
Better to eat an iron ball
 &mdash; glowing, aflame &mdash;
than that, unprincipled &amp;
	unrestrained,
you should eat the alms of the country.

309:
Four things befall the heedless man
who lies down with the wife of another:
a wealth of demerit;
a lack of good sleep;
third, censure;
fourth, hell.

311:
Just as sharp-bladed grass,
if wrongly held,
wounds the very hand that holds it &mdash;
the contemplative life, if wrongly grasped,
drags you down to hell.

328:
If you gain a mature companion &mdash;
a fellow traveler, right-living, enlightened &mdash;
overcoming all dangers
	go with him, gratified,
	mindful.

329:
If you dont gain a mature companion &mdash;
a fellow traveler, right-living, enlightened &mdash;
	go alone
like a king renouncing his kingdom,
like the elephant in the Matanga wilds,
	his herd.

354:
A gift of Dhamma conquers   all gifts;
the taste of Dhamma,            all tastes;
a delight in Dhamma,            all delights;
the ending of craving,      all suffering
	                           &amp; stress.

387:
By day shines the sun;
by night, the moon;
in armor, the warrior;
in jhana, the brahman.
But all day &amp; all night,
every day &amp; every night,
the Awakened One shines
	in splendor.

399:
He endures &mdash; unangered &mdash;
insult, assault, &amp; imprisonment.
His army is strength;
his strength, forbearance:
	hes what I call
	a brahman.
